00:33:18.040 --> 00:33:19.360
up behind the microphone.

00:33:19.360 --> 00:33:21.820
Sir.

00:33:21.820 --> 00:33:26.310
&gt;&gt; Hi. Why did Woodrow Wilson
run for president in 1912;

00:33:26.310 --> 00:33:27.610
what was the motivation?

00:33:27.610 --> 00:33:30.720
And then also, I know
after his presidency

00:33:30.720 --> 00:33:33.580
that you said it was
a downward trajectory

00:33:33.580 --> 00:33:37.240
after the '18 election, and then
in 1920 the republicans romped

00:33:37.240 --> 00:33:40.150
to victory with Harding
and Coolidge.

00:33:40.150 --> 00:33:44.740
What did he think about like
the entire party just collapsing

00:33:44.740 --> 00:33:46.880
in his wake after
he left office?

00:33:46.880 --> 00:33:48.180
&gt;&gt; John Haskell:
That's a great question.

00:33:48.180 --> 00:33:49.540
&gt;&gt; Patricia O'Toole: Yeah,
that is a great question.

00:33:49.540 --> 00:33:53.810
When he ran in 1912, he
was chosen by the democrats

00:33:53.810 --> 00:33:55.720
because he was a fresh face.

00:33:55.720 --> 00:33:57.080
He didn't have any baggage.

00:33:57.080 --> 00:34:02.770
He had only been in politics
for two years and he was a good,

00:34:02.770 --> 00:34:04.870
solid economic progressive.

00:34:04.870 --> 00:34:07.850
You know, we know now that he
wasn't progressive on race,

00:34:07.850 --> 00:34:10.050
he wasn't progressive on
women's issues either.

00:34:10.050 --> 00:34:12.530
He didn't support a
constitutional amendment

00:34:12.530 --> 00:34:15.870
for suffrage until
1918, and he did it then

00:34:15.870 --> 00:34:18.120
because he knew it was going
to happen and he wanted to be

00:34:18.120 --> 00:34:20.590
on the right side of history.

00:34:20.590 --> 00:34:25.700
So he ran because he was
asked to run and he --

00:34:25.700 --> 00:34:28.490
it's a four-way race in 1912.

00:34:28.490 --> 00:34:31.490
He's running against
Taft, the incumbent,

00:34:31.490 --> 00:34:35.270
Theodore Roosevelt charges
in for a third term,

00:34:35.270 --> 00:34:39.940
creates a new party, and
then Eugene Debs ran also.

00:34:39.940 --> 00:34:43.100
So Wilson got 42
percent of the vote

00:34:43.100 --> 00:34:48.940
and that was enough
to get him elected.

00:34:48.940 --> 00:34:54.370
And after the election of 1918,

00:34:54.370 --> 00:34:57.210
when the democratic
party collapsed, he --

00:34:57.210 --> 00:35:00.540
I'm interested in your question
because he mostly didn't --

00:35:00.540 --> 00:35:02.620
he wasn't so focused on that.

00:35:02.620 --> 00:35:08.770
He was focused more on like how
idiotic the republicans were,

00:35:08.770 --> 00:35:13.140
how they refused to face
the realities of the world

00:35:13.140 --> 00:35:16.040
that had been changed
by World War I.

00:35:16.040 --> 00:35:18.150
So he didn't really
blame himself for that.

00:35:18.150 --> 00:35:21.630
And after he left the White
House the only regret he ever

00:35:21.630 --> 00:35:25.750
expressed about his failed fight
for the Treaty of Versailles

00:35:25.750 --> 00:35:29.030
and the League of Nations was
that his timing was wrong.

00:35:29.030 --> 00:35:33.660
He said I think I was ahead of
the American people on this one.

00:35:33.660 --> 00:35:35.640
And there he is, he's a
very sick man, you know,

00:35:35.640 --> 00:35:39.690
he's had this stroke, he's still
paralyzed, but he's imagining,

00:35:39.690 --> 00:35:43.770
both in 1920 and then
in 1922, that he's going

00:35:43.770 --> 00:35:46.140
to run for president again.

00:35:46.140 --> 00:35:48.630
You know, he's clearly
not thinking straight.

00:35:48.630 --> 00:35:52.260
But one of the last things
-- one of the two last --

00:35:52.260 --> 00:35:56.390
two of the last things
that he wrote were a sketch

00:35:56.390 --> 00:35:58.950
of his platform for 1924.

00:35:58.950 --> 00:36:01.940
I mean, this is a man who
is really, really ill.

00:36:01.940 --> 00:36:08.600
And a draft of his
acceptance speech

00:36:08.600 --> 00:36:12.920
after he got the democratic
nomination in 1924.

00:36:12.920 --> 00:36:15.260
He died early in 1924.

00:36:15.260 --> 00:36:18.630
He died in February 3rd, 1924.

00:36:18.630 --> 00:36:23.990
So people ask me how I
feel about Woodrow Wilson

00:36:23.990 --> 00:36:27.730
as a person, you know, what it
was like to write about him,

00:36:27.730 --> 00:36:31.340
because he's not a cozy guy, you
know, you wouldn't like ask him

00:36:31.340 --> 00:36:33.820
out for a beer [laughter].

00:36:33.820 --> 00:36:37.960
And I feel like he was a
really good man who wanted

00:36:37.960 --> 00:36:39.260
to do the right thing,

00:36:39.260 --> 00:36:42.100
but he just didn't
acquire all the skills

00:36:42.100 --> 00:36:45.230
that a politician needs at
the level of the presidency

00:36:45.230 --> 00:36:47.640
to do better than he did.

00:36:47.640 --> 00:36:50.290
But I still admire his
economic achievements

00:36:50.290 --> 00:36:53.510
and I still admire his
ambition for the world to figure

00:36:53.510 --> 00:36:57.430
out a way for global
cooperation.

00:36:57.430 --> 00:36:58.730
Yes, another question?

00:36:58.730 --> 00:37:00.030
&gt;&gt; John Haskell:
We'll go on this side.

00:37:00.030 --> 00:37:01.330
Yeah.

00:37:01.330 --> 00:37:02.630
&gt;&gt; Patricia O'Toole: Oh, okay.

00:37:02.630 --> 00:37:03.930
&gt;&gt; Yes. Thank you
for the presentation.

00:37:03.930 --> 00:37:05.230
I came in here by chance,

00:37:05.230 --> 00:37:06.820
and it's more serendipity
now, so I appreciate that.

00:37:06.820 --> 00:37:10.550
&gt;&gt; Patricia O'Toole: Oh, it's
your lucky day, isn't it?

00:37:10.550 --> 00:37:11.850
&gt;&gt; Yes, it is.

00:37:11.850 --> 00:37:13.150
&gt;&gt; Patricia O'Toole: Yeah.

00:37:13.150 --> 00:37:14.450
Hi.

00:37:14.450 --> 00:37:15.750
&gt;&gt; So how did Wilson
square his moralism

00:37:15.750 --> 00:37:17.830
with the behavior of the allies?

00:37:17.830 --> 00:37:21.240
So thinking about something
like the Balfour Declaration

00:37:21.240 --> 00:37:23.090
or the Sykes-Picot Agreement,

00:37:23.090 --> 00:37:26.480
or other colonialist
activities that --

00:37:26.480 --> 00:37:27.780
&gt;&gt; Patricia O'Toole: Yes.

00:37:27.780 --> 00:37:29.080
Yeah.

00:37:29.080 --> 00:37:30.380
&gt;&gt; came out of the
Paris negotiations?

00:37:30.380 --> 00:37:31.680
&gt;&gt; Patricia O'Toole: Yes.

00:37:31.680 --> 00:37:32.980
That's --

00:37:32.980 --> 00:37:34.280
&gt;&gt; John Haskell: Thank you.

00:37:34.280 --> 00:37:35.950
&gt;&gt; Patricia O'Toole: That's
an excellent question.

00:37:35.950 --> 00:37:39.070
He thought that his
big achievement

00:37:39.070 --> 00:37:44.090
in that regard was they --
you know, the former colonies

00:37:44.090 --> 00:37:50.120
of the other side, the Germans,
were taken away from them

00:37:50.120 --> 00:37:55.390
and rather than just
declare these things,

00:37:55.390 --> 00:37:59.340
rather than divide them up
among the other victors,

00:37:59.340 --> 00:38:03.330
he convinced the allies
at the Peace Conference

00:38:03.330 --> 00:38:07.820
that they should be mandates
of these powers and the powers,

00:38:07.820 --> 00:38:10.140
you know, like France
had some --

00:38:10.140 --> 00:38:13.530
well, I don't want
to get in the weeds,

00:38:13.530 --> 00:38:16.740
but he saw that as an
improvement on imperialism,

00:38:16.740 --> 00:38:19.190
and it was kind of, in
a way, the beginning

00:38:19.190 --> 00:38:21.720
of the end of colonialism.

00:38:21.720 --> 00:38:23.030
So that was his contribution.

00:38:23.030 --> 00:38:27.340
And he didn't like
these things at all.

00:38:27.340 --> 00:38:31.390
But one of the problems

00:38:31.390 --> 00:38:36.040
at the Peace Conference
is the principal powers

00:38:36.040 --> 00:38:39.250
that were negotiating this --
the Germans were not invited

00:38:39.250 --> 00:38:40.600
to the Peace Conference.

00:38:40.600 --> 00:38:43.320
And they had decided among
themselves, the victors,

00:38:43.320 --> 00:38:46.130
that they had to, when
they wrote an article

00:38:46.130 --> 00:38:49.280
into the treaty, it would be
after all of them agreed on it.

00:38:49.280 --> 00:38:51.090
They had to have unanimity,
because they thought

00:38:51.090 --> 00:38:53.610
if they didn't, that
would be open to challenge

00:38:53.610 --> 00:38:55.890
by the defeated powers.

00:38:55.890 --> 00:38:58.930
So Wilson often argued
very intelligently

00:38:58.930 --> 00:39:02.840
and very forcefully for his
point of view, but if the vote

00:39:02.840 --> 00:39:05.850
in the end is three-to-one and
you have this unanimity thing,

00:39:05.850 --> 00:39:07.670
he has to go along
with the other side.

00:39:07.670 --> 00:39:11.530
So he did win some
concessions but not enough.

00:39:11.530 --> 00:39:16.460
So that's, I think, a possibly
good way to look at Wilson

00:39:16.460 --> 00:39:19.520
and the colonialism
after World War I.

00:39:19.520 --> 00:39:20.820
Yeah. Yes.

00:39:20.820 --> 00:39:22.120
&gt;&gt; John Haskell: The
gentleman over here.

00:39:22.120 --> 00:39:23.650
&gt;&gt; So you mentioned how
critical the election

00:39:23.650 --> 00:39:26.400
of November 1918 was.

00:39:26.400 --> 00:39:29.270
I'm just curious about
what was Wilson up to,

00:39:29.270 --> 00:39:39.940
what his priorities were in the
month, six weeks before that,

00:39:39.940 --> 00:39:45.530
October 1918, when he was
trying to win that election

00:39:45.530 --> 00:39:47.520
and negotiate an
armistice and think

00:39:47.520 --> 00:39:48.820
about the future all at once.

00:39:48.820 --> 00:39:50.120
&gt;&gt; Patricia O'Toole: Yes.

00:39:50.120 --> 00:39:53.220
He was certainly more
occupied with thoughts of peace

00:39:53.220 --> 00:39:56.250
than anything else, and
he made a fatal blunder

00:39:56.250 --> 00:39:58.950
in the weeks leading
up to the election.

00:39:58.950 --> 00:40:02.570
He sent an appeal to the
country saying he needed them

00:40:02.570 --> 00:40:06.700
to vote democratic
because he was going to go

00:40:06.700 --> 00:40:11.450
to the Peace Conference and he
had to have the solid backing

00:40:11.450 --> 00:40:13.130
of the American people.

00:40:13.130 --> 00:40:16.570
And the republicans
were insulted,

00:40:16.570 --> 00:40:21.840
and I think justifiably so,
because the republicans,

00:40:21.840 --> 00:40:25.930
when it came to votes
on lending money

00:40:25.930 --> 00:40:32.260
to the allies before we were
in the war and then going --

00:40:32.260 --> 00:40:38.350
you know, building up the Navy
and Army in case we had to be

00:40:38.350 --> 00:40:41.780
in the war, and more
spending itself,

00:40:41.780 --> 00:40:45.410
the republicans were there as
a solid block behind Wilson

00:40:45.410 --> 00:40:48.490
and it was people from
the middle of the country,

00:40:48.490 --> 00:40:50.860
not all of them, or
southerners, who didn't --

00:40:50.860 --> 00:40:52.720
you know, they just thought we
don't have any business going

00:40:52.720 --> 00:40:54.020
beyond the United States.

00:40:54.020 --> 00:40:55.320
So I actually, in my
book, use the word dumbest

00:40:55.320 --> 00:40:56.620
to describe this move of his

00:40:56.620 --> 00:40:57.920
and a couple editors
asked me do you really --

00:40:57.920 --> 00:40:59.220
you know, that's not your
usual tone with things,

00:40:59.220 --> 00:41:00.520
do you really want to use
that word, and I thought

00:41:00.520 --> 00:41:01.820
about it hard and long
and I decided I did.

00:41:01.820 --> 00:41:03.120
I mean, it was really
dumb [laughter].

00:41:03.120 --> 00:41:04.420
So --

00:41:04.420 --> 00:41:07.510
and his wife begged him
not to send this out.

00:41:07.510 --> 00:41:09.950
I think Colonel House begged
him, too, not to send it out,

00:41:09.950 --> 00:41:15.810
but he did, and the
rest was very sad.

00:41:15.810 --> 00:41:17.170
Yeah. Yes.

00:41:17.170 --> 00:41:18.990
&gt;&gt; Well, I planned to be here

00:41:18.990 --> 00:41:21.090
because teaching
the Middle East,

00:41:21.090 --> 00:41:23.320
talking about Woodrow
Wilson was very important.

00:41:23.320 --> 00:41:26.390
So to follow up on my
colleague's question,

00:41:26.390 --> 00:41:31.060
the King-Crane Commission, would
you like to comment on that,

00:41:31.060 --> 00:41:35.250
that he sent to the Middle
East to ask -- this was 1919.

00:41:35.250 --> 00:41:40.510
Was that kind of part of, again,
this moralist, principled man

00:41:40.510 --> 00:41:43.820
who wanted to ask the people
who lived in that part

00:41:43.820 --> 00:41:45.900
of the world what they wanted?

00:41:45.900 --> 00:41:47.490
&gt;&gt; Patricia O'Toole:
You know, he was so busy

00:41:47.490 --> 00:41:50.930
at the Paris Peace Conference
that he took along this group

00:41:50.930 --> 00:41:52.230
of people called "The Inquiry".

00:41:52.230 --> 00:41:53.530
Have you read about
them and their work?

00:41:53.530 --> 00:41:54.830
[ Inaudible comment ]

00:41:54.830 --> 00:41:56.130
It was a very good book --

00:41:56.130 --> 00:41:57.430
&gt;&gt; Okay.

00:41:57.430 --> 00:41:58.730
&gt;&gt; by a man named
Lawrence Gelfand

00:41:58.730 --> 00:42:00.030
that details what they're doing.

00:42:00.030 --> 00:42:02.320
So a lot of smart people who
were expert in different parts

00:42:02.320 --> 00:42:04.320
of the world, cartographers,
geographers,

00:42:04.320 --> 00:42:07.680
economists, and so on.

00:42:07.680 --> 00:42:08.980
&gt;&gt; Right.

00:42:08.980 --> 00:42:10.280
&gt;&gt; Patricia O'Toole:
And the answer

00:42:10.280 --> 00:42:11.580
to your question is
probably in there,

00:42:11.580 --> 00:42:13.600
but he took their advice
on a lot of things.

00:42:13.600 --> 00:42:19.160
So if this idea had come to
him, he would have said, well,

00:42:19.160 --> 00:42:21.480
what do the men at The
Inquiry think about this,

00:42:21.480 --> 00:42:23.550
and would have followed
their advice.

00:42:23.550 --> 00:42:25.370
So it's something
that really didn't get

00:42:25.370 --> 00:42:26.790
on my radar very much.

00:42:26.790 --> 00:42:28.290
I'm sorry I can't be more help.

00:42:28.290 --> 00:42:29.590
&gt;&gt; No. That's fine.

00:42:29.590 --> 00:42:30.890
&gt;&gt; Patricia O'Toole: Yeah.

00:42:30.890 --> 00:42:32.190
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:42:32.190 --> 00:42:33.490
Thank you.

00:42:33.490 --> 00:42:34.790
&gt;&gt; John Haskell: Ma'am.

00:42:34.790 --> 00:42:36.090
&gt;&gt; Patricia O'Toole: Yes.

00:42:36.090 --> 00:42:37.390
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:42:37.390 --> 00:42:38.690
I was wondering who were his
mentors, as maybe starting

00:42:38.690 --> 00:42:39.990
in college, in that area.

00:42:39.990 --> 00:42:41.290
Who did he look up to?

00:42:41.290 --> 00:42:43.510
And then, it's maybe
a different question,

00:42:43.510 --> 00:42:46.420
but who did he listen to?

00:42:46.420 --> 00:42:47.720
That's what --

00:42:47.720 --> 00:42:49.020
&gt;&gt; Patricia O'Toole: Wow.

00:42:49.020 --> 00:42:50.870
Yeah. Yes.

00:42:50.870 --> 00:42:53.470
His mentors, the statesmen

00:42:53.470 --> 00:42:57.820
who inspired him were
the great orators.

00:42:57.820 --> 00:43:04.530
So, you know, Lincoln, Calhoun,
Webster, in the United States.

00:43:04.530 --> 00:43:10.220
And then in England it
was Sir William Gladstone

00:43:10.220 --> 00:43:14.340
and a guy named Cobb,
and they were all people

00:43:14.340 --> 00:43:16.910
who were really great
speakers who managed to --

00:43:16.910 --> 00:43:18.990
you know, managed
to sway parliament

00:43:18.990 --> 00:43:20.520
to do something or other.

00:43:20.520 --> 00:43:23.550
So those were his models.

00:43:23.550 --> 00:43:28.350
And then the question of who
he listened to, he got more

00:43:28.350 --> 00:43:30.350
and more isolated
as he was president.

00:43:30.350 --> 00:43:34.080
He was a better listener
early on.

00:43:34.080 --> 00:43:38.070
His treasury secretary,
William Gibbs McAdoo,

00:43:38.070 --> 00:43:42.400
became his son-in-law
and Wilson did --

00:43:42.400 --> 00:43:46.240
because he's in the family,
so he would listen to McAdoo,

00:43:46.240 --> 00:43:49.100
but he really didn't
like him very much.

00:43:49.100 --> 00:43:51.150
And he listened to Colonel House

00:43:51.150 --> 00:43:54.380
up to 1918, and that's
mainly it.

00:43:54.380 --> 00:43:55.770
Yes. Thank you.

00:43:55.770 --> 00:43:57.410
&gt;&gt; John Haskell: Well thank
you very much, Patricia.

00:43:57.410 --> 00:43:58.710
&gt;&gt; Patricia O'Toole:
Thank you, John.

00:43:58.710 --> 00:44:00.010
&gt;&gt; John Haskell: This
has been fascinating.

00:44:00.010 --> 00:44:01.310
&gt;&gt; Patricia O'Toole:
Thank you very much.

00:44:01.310 --> 00:44:02.610
It was a great interview.

00:44:02.610 --> 00:44:03.910
&gt;&gt; John Haskell:
Thanks for joining us.

